  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Somalia is a country prone to recurrent droughts due to irregular rainfall patterns and the effects of climate change. In both Puntland and Somaliland territories, the population mostly depends on agro-pastoralism and livestock, which have been affected by the drought, reducing access to food and impacting on their nutritional/health status. The farming situation has since deteriorated due tothe lack of rains that helps in cultivation. Water sources of these communities are shallow wells of which most are damaged and need rehabilitation.
An estimated 6.2  million people, about half of the population, are currently in need of humanitarian assistance in Somalia. The current drought was declared in Somalia in 2016 . A significant degradation in food security, nutrition, WASH and health conditions has been recorded across the country since the start of the current drought.
This GERC Project focuses on provision of livelihoods training (CAHW training, milk storage training), Food Security (Unconditional Cash Transfer), Sanitation (latrine construction), Water provision (solar study, and solarising borehole), and hygiene promotion (lifestraw filter distribution, CHV training, environmental cleaning campaigns etc.)</narrative>
  </description>
